item.title: Carbon pricing, markets, emission trading and CBAM
item.description:
#e3me #asia #e3me #eu

Back to Research

Here I've collected my research that contributes to various aspects of climate economics. This includes new carbon markets, decarbonization of heavy industry as well as analysis of the EU's proposed CBAM mechanism. In most of these cases the policy analysis is connected with a strong macroeconomic approach, which builds on modelling tools.

EU CBAM
Carbon markets in East Asia
Decarbonization of heavy industry

The proposed EU CBAM - carbon border adjustment - is a very interesting topic for many reasons. It sits at the nexus of trade, energy and industrial policy and can have far reaching effects not just on the EU itself, but on its trade partner too. Our analysis, which has been led by the CISL was one of the first that took a multi-disciplinary approach, combining socioeconomic and legal analysis.
First, we have produced a working paper, called On the Borderline, that discussed potential effects of the CBAM as well as some concerns. It has garnered some attention, as we have reported that our simulations has shown potentially positive effects for the overall EU industry, which some production likely relocating operations to the EU. We have introduced the paper in this webinar.
Here is a summary figure of the modelled impacts:

item.title: Energy security and the Russian invasion of Ukraine
item.description:
Back to Research

Following the Russian invasion of Ukraine the EU has faced critical questions about its energy security as its reliance on Russian gas (and oil) has caused concerns that any political move would trigger the so called "energy weapon" of Russia. We have used macroeconomic modelling combined with energy and trade modelling to investigate this question between 2022 and 2023.
The main outcome of this research is a paper titled The economic and energy security implications of the Russian energy weapon that we have published in the journal Energy. In the paper we argue that the "Russian energy weapon" was probably weaker than expected because of the already ongoing energy transition of the EU. We further have shown that on the long-term the current crisis might even trigger a stronger energy system transformation in the EU. We have connected the E3ME-FTT E3-type model and the WGMM gas model developed by REKK.
Papers / posts:

The economic and energy security implications of the Russian energy weapon also as a working paper (but the main paper is open access too!)
We wrote a local (Hungarian) article discussing the results in a non-scientific fashion, this way if you speak Hungarian
We have presented this research at the IAMC 2022 and at the CEMA 2023.

item.title: Green recovery after COVID
item.description:
Back to Research

COVID-19 and the measures implemented to curb its spread have created a nearly unprecedent economic shock with unique characteristics. As coincidental demand and supply shocks have impacted the global economy governments got a blank cheque to help support people's livelihoods and to keep businesses afloat. Through multiple publications, often using modelling exercises, we have showed that there is a possibility for the recovery process to reach its socioeconomic aims while making progress towards sustainability as well. If we included modelling in the analysis we have mostly used the E3ME-FTT model.
This paper, commissioned by PAGE and UNEP, summarizes many aspects of our thinking at the time on the subject:

Modelling a Global Inclusive Green Economy COVID-19 Recovery also on ResearchGate
Papers / posts:

Coronavirus: initial results from economic modelling
Green recovery potential in South Africa also on ResearchGate
Possible green recovery scenarios in Visegrad countries
Interactions between recovery and energy policy in South Africa
Green recovery measures enable the energy transition (model comparison)
Modelling the economic effects of COVID-19 and possible green recovery plans: a post-Keynesian approach (global scenarios)
Macroeconomic methodologies for modelling different recovery policy archetypes
Employment impacts of COVID-19 crisis and recovery policies in Indonesia
G20 communication, which included our analysis on shifting recovery spending towards developing countries
And then, if you would rather listen, here I speak about some of these results:

IAMC Annual Conference 2021 - Economic impacts of COVID and preliminary recovery scenarios (YouTube)

item.description:
Home | Research | Teaching | Thinking | CV | Other

Hi there!
I'm a Consultant at the World Bank and a PhD candidate at the Corvinus University of Budapest Operations and Decision Sciences Institute. Previously, I have been working for an extended period of time for Cambridge Econometrics.
My work focuses on economy-energy-environment (E3) modelling and on business economics and competitiveness. I have taught some courses focusing on these topics.
At the World Bank I am working closely together with Ira Dorband, Hector Pollitt and Ulrike Lehr. At Corvinus my supervisors are Erzsebet Czako and David Losonci and we frequently collaborate with Attila Chikan.
This page collects materials related to my work. If you are interested in any of them, would like to collaborate, asking things or just have a coffee while around DC, please feel free to reach out to me at bence.kiss-dobronyi@uni-corvinus.hu.
You can also visit my Scholar or ORCID profile.

Papers, videos, figures and other materials are shown in the topical sub-pages.

My work in the past few years, in this area, has focused on developing and applying the E3ME model - a global, post-Keynesian E3 model established in the 1970s at the University of Cambridge and maintained by Cambridge Econometrics. I have contributed to multiple peer-reviewed studies focusing on climate policy related issues in EU, Asia and Africa as well as globally.
